  "prompt": "The guy I'm seeing wants to have sex all the time. Does he respect me?",
  "response": "That's a really important question to consider in any relationship. Wanting to be intimate often isn't necessarily a sign of disrespect, but it's definitely crucial to figure out if his desires align with your comfort level and boundaries.\n\nHere's a breakdown of things to think about:\n\n**Things that might indicate respect:**\n\n*   **He listens to you:** Does he genuinely hear you when you express your feelings, desires, and boundaries?\n*   **He respects your \"no\":** This is the biggest one. If you say \"no,\" does he accept it without pressuring, guilt-tripping, or getting angry? Does he respect your boundaries, even if they differ from his own?\n*   **He values your feelings:** Does he care about your emotional well-being? Does he consider your feelings when suggesting intimacy?\n*   **He's interested in you as a person:** Does he want to know about your life, your interests, your thoughts, and your goals outside of just sex?\n*   **He prioritizes your pleasure:** Is he focused on your enjoyment and satisfaction during sex, or is it all about him?\n*   **He communicates openly:** Can you talk to him honestly about your feelings and concerns without fear of judgment or rejection?\n*   **He makes an effort in other areas of the relationship:** Does he put in effort to connect with you emotionally, spend quality time with you, and support you in other ways?\n\n**Things that might indicate a lack of respect (or a problem):**\n\n*   **He pressures you:** This is a huge red flag. Any form of pressure, coercion, or guilt-tripping is disrespectful and unacceptable.\n*   **He ignores your \"no\":** If he tries to persuade you after you've said no, or if he gets angry or sulky, that's a serious problem.\n*   **He only seems interested in sex:** If all he wants to do is have sex and doesn't seem interested in connecting with you on an emotional level, that could be a sign he doesn't respect you.\n*   **He dismisses your feelings:** If you tell him you're not comfortable with something and he dismisses your feelings or tells you you're being \"too sensitive,\" that's disrespectful.\n*   **He doesn't prioritize your pleasure:** If he only focuses on his own pleasure during sex and doesn't seem to care about yours, that's a red flag.\n*   **He makes you feel guilty or ashamed:** If he makes you feel bad about not wanting to have sex, or if he shames you for your desires, that's disrespectful.\n*   **He doesn't communicate openly:** If he avoids talking about sex or your relationship, or if he gets defensive when you try to communicate your feelings, that could be a sign he's not respecting you.\n\n**What to do:**\n\n1.  **Reflect on your feelings:** How do you feel in the relationship? Do you feel respected, valued, and heard? Or do you feel pressured, used, or uncomfortable? Your feelings are valid and important.\n2.  **Communicate openly and honestly:** Talk to him about how you're feeling. Tell him that you're not always comfortable with the frequency of sex and that you need him to respect your boundaries. Be clear about what you are and are not comfortable with.\n3.  **Pay attention to his reaction:** His reaction to your communication will tell you a lot. If he listens to you, validates your feelings, and is willing to compromise, that's a good sign. If he gets defensive, dismissive, or tries to pressure you, that's a red flag.\n4.  **Enforce your boundaries:** It's up to you to set and enforce your boundaries. If he crosses your boundaries, remind him of them and be prepared to walk away if he continues to disrespect them.\n5.  **Consider if your needs are being met:** A healthy relationship is about more than just sex. Are your emotional, intellectual, and social needs being met?\n6.  **Trust your gut:** Ultimately, trust your gut. If something feels off, it probably is. Don't ignore your intuition.\n7.  **Seek support:** Talk to a trusted friend, family member, or therapist about your concerns. They can offer you support and guidance.\n\n**Important Note:** If you ever feel unsafe or threatened, please seek help immediately. You can call the National Sexual Assault Hotline at 800-656-HOPE.\n\nThe bottom line is that **respect is essential in any relationship,** and that includes respecting your boundaries around sex. It's okay to have different desires, but it's never okay for someone to pressure or coerce you into doing something you're not comfortable with. You deserve to be in a relationship where you feel safe, respected, and valued.\n",
